<h3><a href="https://www.pilotonline.com/opinion/letters/vp-ed-lets-0426-20220425-lmoxhcsptzenzhfybqkcwthauu-story.html" target="_blank">Letters for April 26: If the governor wants to make Virginia great, address slumlords</a></h3>
<p><h2>Support Virginians</h2>
<p>Re &ldquo;<a href="https://www.pilotonline.com/government/virginia/vp-nw-statehouse-housing-politics-20220410-qqwf6cxi35fsjopxe72lztbrda-story.html" target="_blank">Housing bill could empower localities to take action against negligent landlords: &lsquo;You shouldn&rsquo;t treat somebody like this&rsquo;</a>&rdquo; (April 10) and &ldquo;<a href="https://www.pilotonline.com/government/virginia/vp-nw-statehouse-politics-democrats-20220412-sjqphzwilzb7pip6q3f4dwgpgy-story.html" target="_blank">Democrats &lsquo;stunned&rsquo; as Youngkin vetoes 25 bipartisan bills &mdash; including 3 from Hampton Roads lawmakers</a>&rdquo; (April 12) and &ldquo;<a href="https://www.pilotonline.com/opinion/editorials/vp-ed-editorial-beagle-bills-0414-20220413-n7z37r5vq5cxjfnyix27b3vkpu-story.html" target="_blank">Dogs bring officials together</a>&rdquo; (Our Views, April 13): Does the governor really think more about dogs than people? Two recent articles and an editorial imply that he does.</p>
<p>The first article was about a bill that was passed by the House and was awaiting the governor&rsquo;s signature. He didn&rsquo;t sign it. It would have given local authorities power to sue negligent landlords who don&rsquo;t maintain their properties. The disguising conditions described by a tenant of a Newport News apartment were a sample of conditions targeted by the bill that had support of many groups, including the city of Newport News and the Virginia Apartment Management Association.</p>
<p>In the second article about Gov. Glenn Youngkin&rsquo;s veto, Youngkin said in a statement, &ldquo;My goal as governor is to make Virginia the best place to live, work, and raise a family and the bills I vetoed today reaffirm that commitment.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The editorial was about Youngkin signing a bill to protect dogs. The Editorial Board stated, &ldquo;it is reassuring whenever lawmakers recognize an egregious problem and move swiftly, together, to address it thoughtfully.&rdquo;</p>
<div id="nativo_646518">
<div id="ntv1111510-0-26503" data-confiant-id="CONFIANT_AD_SUFFIX_5155">
<div>
<div>The tenant who shared her story said it best, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m trying to be a voice for everybody who may be scared to say stuff. ... You shouldn&rsquo;t treat somebody like this.&rdquo; State leaders should be given a second chance. Del. Cia Price could reintroduce her bill, have the House pass it, and have the governor sign it reaffirming his commitment by correcting his egregious error.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><em>Bob Volpe, Norfolk</em></p></p>
