<div class="news-item">
<span class="newsDate">Tuesday, April 19, 2022 2:48 PM</span>
<h3><a href="https://vpm.org/news/articles/31445/youngkin-vetoes-bipartisan-bill-designed-to-rein-in-slumlords" target="_blank">Youngkin vetoes bipartisan bill designed to rein in slumlords</a></h3>
<p><p>The horror stories have cropped up from tenants across the state: no heat, holes in the walls, rotten floors and flooded kitchens. In cases ranging from&nbsp;<a href="https://www.wric.com/news/local-news/henrico-county/hundreds-of-violations-found-in-henricos-glenwood-farms-in-4-year-span-its-unacceptable/" target="_blank">Glenwood Farms</a>&nbsp;in Henrico to&nbsp;<a href="https://www.13newsnow.com/article/news/local/mycity/newport-news/aqua-vista-apartments-in-newport-news-slapped-with-300-violations/291-96bce655-2978-4a77-94fc-c63c8f957e3c" target="_blank">Aqua Vista</a>&nbsp;in Newport News, residents&rsquo; complaints have continued even after property owners have been slapped with hundreds of code citations.</p>
<p>Housing advocates say legislation passed by the General Assembly on a bipartisan vote would have helped rein in the most negligent landlords. Now they&rsquo;re questioning Gov. Glenn Youngkin&rsquo;s veto of the&nbsp;<a href="https://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?221+sum+HB802" target="_blank">bill</a>&nbsp;from Del. Cia Price (D-Newport News), which received no critical testimony in committee and was backed by both the Virginia Poverty Law Center and the Virginia Apartment and Management Association.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This is creating a safe space in Virginia for slumlords,&rdquo; Price says. &ldquo;I don't know what the governor was thinking but that's what the end result will be.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Part of the problem now is that cities and counties don&rsquo;t have great tools at their disposal to deal with absentee landlords, according to Christie Marra, director of housing advocacy at the VPLC. Their main mode of enforcement is citing landlords for code violations, which, if they don&rsquo;t address, can result in fines as low as $50.</p></p>
