<div class="news-item">
<span class="newsDate">Sunday, April 10, 2022 11:26 AM</span>
<h3><a href="https://www.pilotonline.com/government/virginia/vp-nw-statehouse-housing-politics-20220410-qqwf6cxi35fsjopxe72lztbrda-story.html" target="_blank">Housing bill could empower localities to take action against negligent landlords: ‘You shouldn’t treat somebody like this’</a></h3>
<p><p>Del. Cia Price, who introduced the bill, said she worked on the measure after hearing from constituents who couldn&rsquo;t get landlords to fix a range of problems, including mold, leaks, rodent infestations and broken heat or air conditioning.</p>
<div id="outstream_2_wrapper">
<div>
<div>&nbsp;&ldquo;It&rsquo;s really heart-breaking because when I would go into their apartments and meet with them &mdash; a lot of the kids who live in these apartments have respiratory issues,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;... I&rsquo;m not sure if it was caused by their environment, but it&rsquo;s definitely exacerbated by their environment.&rdquo;</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>But the Newport News Democrat said localities have limited options when it comes to taking action against landlords; they can either issue fines or condemn the buildings.</p>
<p>Fines aren&rsquo;t always effective because they can often be less costly than large-scale improvements, Price said. And condemning buildings can exacerbate problems with housing shortages or homelessness.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This bill would allow them to sue to get the actual things fixed, not just give a fine or condemn the apartment,&rdquo; she said.</p></p>
