<h3><a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/jobs-prison-conviction-collateral-consequences-rcna7247" target="_blank">Banned from jobs: People released from prison fight laws that keep punishing them</a></h3>
<p><p>In Virginia, the barrier crime law started two decades ago when legislators unanimously agreed to require background checks for some jobs involving kids. &ldquo;It started out with a good idea,&rdquo; said state Sen. John Edwards, a Democrat from Roanoke who voted for the bill&nbsp;<a href="https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/37.2-416/">in 1999</a>. &ldquo;Then it kind of evolved into this monster that we have now that&rsquo;s overly broad without any way of getting relief.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>Last year, after Democrats took over the state Legislature and the governor&rsquo;s office, legislators created a&nbsp;<a href="http://dls.virginia.gov/interim_studies_barrier_crimes.html">subcommittee</a>&nbsp;to study the issue, led by Edwards and Del. Marcia Price.&nbsp; &ldquo;We found that there is really no proof that we needed these barrier crimes,&rdquo; Price said. &ldquo;There was no proof they were keeping people safe, and it was actually doing damage.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>In January, legislators are scheduled to consider a measure that could soften the law and create a waiver system. If it passes, it could give Carey the chance to go back to the work he does best.&nbsp; &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t really care if it happens for me or not,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I just want it to happen for everyone behind me.&rdquo;</p>
<div>
<p>(click to read full story)</p>
</div></p>
</div>
