<h3><a href="https://vpm.org/news/articles/24332/virginia-eviction-protections-could-be-extended-as-filings-rise" target="_blank">Virginia Eviction Protections Could Be Extended as Filings Rise</a></h3>
<p><p>Right now, it&rsquo;s optional for landlords to apply on behalf of tenants. Democratic lawmakers like Cia Price want to make it mandatory, as it was from late November through June. That setup won praise from the&nbsp;<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/25/opinion/eviction-moratorium-covid-philadelphia.html" target="_blank">New York Times&rsquo; editorial board</a>&nbsp;as a model for other states where the funds have languished.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is unconscionable that there would be evictions when the money is there,&rdquo; Price said.</p>
<p>So far, the fund has helped over 48,000 households with over $300 million in rent money; nearly $700 million remains left to disperse. The budget proposed by Gov. Ralph Northam that is currently under consideration by the General Assembly would allow the program to be extended through June 2022 or until the funds are exhausted.</p></p>
