<h3><a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/voting-rights-states-democrats-b1889668.html" target="_blank">‘The long term fight’: How Democrats plan to save voting rights</a></h3>
<p><p>Within the last two years, the state&rsquo;s Democrat-controlled General Assembly and Governor Ralph Northam have secured no-excuse mail-in ballots, repealed a restrictive voter ID law, enacted automatic voter registration and made Election Day a state holiday &ndash; marking a radical expansion of voting rights that advocates now are fighting to protect, or risk undermining generational progress against a tide of suppressive voting laws across the US. &ldquo;It can go away,&rdquo; said the bill&rsquo;s author, Virginia Representative Marcia Price. &ldquo;I think people sometimes don&rsquo;t really understand how fragile this process really is,&rdquo; she told&nbsp;<em>The Independent.&nbsp;</em>&ldquo;In my eyes, America&rsquo;s democracy started in 1965 and not a day before that. What are we doing to protect it, feed it and nurture it? I think the next step is continuing to protect the progress that we&rsquo;ve made and fighting back against the big lie.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not blind faith or trust in humanity that got us the Voting Rights Act [of 1965],&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;It was literal blood, sweat and tears. &hellip; I don&rsquo;t have the luxury to believe in the best in humanity. I need the laws to protect my rights, my community&rsquo;s rights and everybody&rsquo;s rights. I have hope in the people who have put their lives on the line because we&rsquo;ve had to do that for generations to get the changes that we needed. That is what keeps us going.&rdquo;</p>
