<span class="newsDate">Wednesday, June 23, 2021 11:33 AM</span>
<h3><a href="https://www.dailypress.com/news/crime/dp-nw-marijuana-changes-conversations-20210622-azba6cpidnf43k7c4kn7c3nne4-story.html" target="_blank">Virginia’s marijuana reform needs work, some say. So a delegate and a defense lawyer will discuss the new law.</a></h3>
<p><div data-type="text">
<div>
<p data-page="1" data-item-type="depthscroll" data-item-id="depth_scroll_top" data-item-number="top">A Newport News state delegate and a prominent local criminal defense lawyer will talk about Virginia&rsquo;s marijuana legalization on Wednesday evening in a Zoom call. The discussion &mdash; open to the public &mdash; is part of a new &ldquo;Conversations with the Clerk&rdquo; series sponsored by Newport News Clerk of Circuit Court Angela Reason. The online discussion between Reason, Del. Marcia &ldquo;Cia&rdquo; Price, D-Newport News, and attorney Timothy Clancy will begin at 6 p.m. Price was heavily involved in the recent effort to legalize marijuana, while Clancy is an expert on the current state laws on the issue.</p>
<p>The Zoom ID to get access to the discussion is 844-4057-6466. The Virginia General Assembly voted earlier this year to legalize the simple possession of marijuana for adults ages 21 and older. That&rsquo;s up to an ounce, with no intent to distribute, and adults can grow up to four plants per household. But the law, which goes into effect July 1, is still considered confusing and a work in progress because it&rsquo;s still against the law to both buy and sell pot. It&rsquo;s also still illegal to use it in public or while driving. Lawmakers are still hashing out the details of how the marijuana marketplace will be formed and regulated.</p>
</div>
</div></p>
</div>
